The current implementations of IConvertible.ToType do not handle conversion to type object. We were not expecting ToType to be called with a conversionType argument of type object (after all you can simply cast to object), but it turns out this is legal so we should support it.

The following code snippet currently throws an InvalidCastException:

{code}
var id = ObjectId.GenerateNewId();
var obj = ((IConvertible)id).ToType(typeof(object), null);
{code}

This native Mongo shell command works fine

{code}
db.createCollection("noautoid", { autoIndexId: false })
{code}

i.e. a collection created with no index on `_id`.

But I cannot achieve the same using

{code}
CollectionOptionsBuilder.SetAutoIndexId(false)
{code}

The index is always created.

I took a look at the code:

MongoDB.Driver\Builders\CollectionOptionsBuilder.cs(104):

{code}
        public CollectionOptionsBuilder SetAutoIndexId(bool value)
        {
            if (value)
            {
                _document["autoIndexId"] = value;
            }
            else
            {
                _document.Remove("autoIndexId");
            }
            return this;
        }
{code}
It looks like `SetAutoIndexId(false)` makes the option removed, so that the
default is used which is presumably `true`.

Perhaps the correct code would be

{code}
        public CollectionOptionsBuilder SetAutoIndexId(bool value)
        {
            if (value)
            {
                _document["autoIndexId"] = value;
            }
            return this;
        }
{code}

which adds the option `{ autoIndexId: false }` explicitly, like the Mongo shell
command does and works as desired.
